  <Name>k__BackingField: Titus
  fancyName: 
  nickname: tit
  version: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 69cda689d36a6b64ca4a020e1d829e9f, type: 2}
  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Introduction'
      title: Introduction
      number: 1
      content: "From Paul, God\u2019s willing slave [[COMMENT(0)]] and an apostle
        of Jesus, the Anointed One, to Titus.  I\u2019m writing to you to further
        the faith  of God\u2019s chosen ones and lead them to the full knowledge
        of the truth that leads to godliness, "
      comments:
      - number: 1:1
        content: "  Or \u201Cbondservant.\u201D      Although the name Titus is not
          found until v.  , it is included here to enhance the understanding of Paul\u2019s
          introduction.      Or \u201Caccording to the faith of God\u2019s elect.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'which rests on the hope of eternal life. God, who never lies, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        has promised this before time began. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:2
        content: '  Paul is making quite a statement in this verse. Zeus was said
          to have been born in Crete, and Cretans were known to be liars (). So Paul
          is saying to the Cretans that our God is greater than Zeus and he never
          lies!    '
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: In his own time he unveiled his word through the preaching of the
        gospel, which was entrusted to me by the command of God our Life Giver. [[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: 1:3
        content: "  As translated from the Aramaic. The Greek is \u201CSavior.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: Qualities of Church Leaders'
      title: Qualities of Church Leaders
      number: 4
      content: Titus, you are my true son in the faith we share. May grace and peace
        descend to you from God the Father and our Savior, the Anointed One, Jesus!
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'The reason I stationed you in Crete [[COMMENT(0)]] was so that you
        could set things in order and complete what was left unfinished,  and to
        raise up and appoint church elders  in every city, just as I had instructed
        you. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:5
        content: "  A Greek island in the Aegean Sea. Paul\u2019s ship had stopped
          on the way to Rome at Fair Havens, a small harbor on the southern coast
          of Crete ().      The unfinished work would be bringing believers into
          maturity in Christ and raising up godly, qualified leaders who could teach
          the church and lead it forward.      Or \u201Cordain elders.\u201D This
          is the Greek word  , which means \u201Csenior leaders.\u201D These are
          church elders who would function as overseers, teachers, and shepherds
          of God\u2019s flock. The same Greek word is used for women in  . Although
          generally assumed to be male in the cultural context of that day, there
          is nothing to indicate that    is gender exclusive. The church elder is
          called an \u201Coverseer\u201D (or \u201Cbishop\u201D) in v.  , which indicates
          that both terms speak of the same office and are synonymous.    "
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Each of them must be above reproach, devoted solely to his wife,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] whose children are believers and not rebellious or out of
        control. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:6
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe husband of one wife\u201D or \u201Cmarried only
          once.\u201D    "
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "The overseer, since he serves God\u2019s household, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        must be someone of blameless character and not be opinionated or short-tempered.
        He must not be a drunkard or violent or greedy. "
      comments:
      - number: 1:7
        content: "  Or \u201CGod\u2019s steward.\u201D    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Instead he should be one who is known for his hospitality and a lover
        of goodness. [[COMMENT(0)]] He should be recognized as one who is fair-minded,
        pure-hearted, and self-controlled. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:8
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201Cone who nurtures goodness\u201D
          (in others). We would say, \u201Cone who brings out the best in others.\u201D    "
    - name: '9: False Teachers'
      title: False Teachers
      number: 9
      content: He must have a firm grasp of the trustworthy message that he has been
        taught. This will enable him to both encourage others with healthy teachings
        and provide convincing answers to those who oppose his message.
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "There are many wayward people, smooth talkers, and deceivers\u2014especially
        the converts from Judaism. [[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: 1:10
        content: "  Or \u201Cthose of the circumcision\u201D (group), i.e., Jewish
          converts. Paul is pointing to three types of people who will refute and
          argue with church leaders: rebels, empty talkers, and deceivers. The leaders
          (elders) must be faithful to the Scriptures in order to correct them and
          set them in order.    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'They must be silenced [[COMMENT(0)]] because they are disrupting
        entire families with their corrupt teachings, all for their dishonest greed. '
      comments:
      - number: 1:11
        content: "  Or \u201Creined in.\u201D The Greek word    is used for the reins
          of a horse.    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "A certain one of them, one of their own prophets, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        said, \u201CThose Cretans are nothing but liars, worthless beasts, and lazy
        gluttons.\u201D   "
      comments:
      - number: 1:12
        content: "  Although the Greek uses the word  , it is not used here in the
          biblical sense of a \u201Cprophet\u201D of God, for the author of this
          proverb was a pagan.      A quote from the Oracles of Epimenides, a six-century
          BC poet. The first line is quoted from The    by Callimachus.  "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'He certainly knew what he was talking about! For this reason, correct
        them thoroughly so that their lives will line up with the truths of our faith. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: Instruct them not to pay any attention to Jewish myths or follow the
        teachings of those who reject the truth.
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "It\u2019s true that all is pure to those who have pure hearts, but
        to the corrupt unbelievers nothing is pure. Their minds and consciences are
        defiled. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: They claim to know God, but by their actions they deny him. They are
        disgusting, disobedient, and disqualified from doing anything good.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Character Consistent with Godliness'
      title: Character Consistent with Godliness
      number: 1
      content: 'Your duty is to teach them to embrace a lifestyle that is consistent
        with sound doctrine. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: Lead the male elders [[COMMENT(0)]] into disciplined lives full of
        dignity and self-control. Urge them to have a solid faith, generous love,
        and patient endurance.
      comments:
      - number: 2:2
        content: "  Or \u201Cold men.\u201D    "
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Likewise with the female elders, [[COMMENT(0)]] lead them into lives
        free from gossip and drunkenness and to be teachers of beautiful things.   '
      comments:
      - number: 2:3
        content: "  Or \u201Cold women.\u201D      As translated from the Aramaic.
          The Greek is \u201Cgood things.\u201D    "
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'This will enable them to teach the younger women [[COMMENT(0)]] to
        love their husbands, to love their children, '
      comments:
      - number: 2:4
        content: "  Paul is contrasting the \u201Celders\u201D with the \u201Cyounger\u201D
          (Gr.  ) and could possibly be referring to those who are newly converted.    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: and to be self-controlled and pure, taking care of their household
        and being devoted to [[COMMENT(0)]] their husbands. By doing these things
        the word of God will not be discredited.
      comments:
      - number: 2:5
        content: "  Or \u201Csupportive of.\u201D    "
    - name: '6: Be an Example'
      title: Be an Example
      number: 6
      content: Likewise, guide the younger men into living disciplined lives for
        Christ.
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Above all, set yourself apart as a model of a life nobly lived. With
        dignity, demonstrate integrity in all that you teach. [[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: 2:7
        content: "  \u201CIntegrity in all that you teach\u201D would imply serious
          study of God\u2019s Word and its personal application in our lives, and
          not teaching impulsively from one\u2019s opinion, which only leads to arguments
          and divisions. This kind of integrity gives someone the right to be heard.    "
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'Bring a clear, wholesome message [[COMMENT(0)]] that cannot be condemned,
        and then your critics will be embarrassed, with nothing bad to say about
        us. '
      comments:
      - number: 2:8
        content: "  Or \u201Cwith sound speech.\u201D      Paul and Titus were a
          team. If one were to err, it would affect the other.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Servants [[COMMENT(0)]] are to be supportive of  their masters and
        do what is pleasing in every way. They are not to be argumentative '
      comments:
      - number: 2:9
        content: "  Or \u201Cbondservants.\u201D      Or \u201Csubmitted to.\u201D    "
    - name: "10: God\u2019s Grace, Our Motivation"
      title: "God\u2019s Grace, Our Motivation"
      number: 10
      content: nor steal [[COMMENT(0)]] but prove themselves to be completely loyal
        and trustworthy. By doing this they will advertise  through all that they
        do the beautiful teachings of God our Savior.
      comments:
      - number: 2:10
        content: "  Businesses today lose millions of dollars to employee theft.
          Believers are to be meticulously honest in the workplace.      Or \u201Cadorn
          [beautify] the doctrine of God.\u201D    "
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "God\u2019s marvelous grace [[COMMENT(0)]] has manifested in person,
        bringing salvation for everyone.   "
      comments:
      - number: 2:11
        content: "  Grace extends God\u2019s kindness and love to us every moment
          and makes us \u201Cworthy\u201D of his acceptance. Grace is unconditional,
          unmerited, indescribable favor from God.      That is, grace has revealed
          a salvation available for everyone. Or \u201CGod\u2019s marvelous grace
          has appeared to all, bringing salvation.\u201D    "
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'This same grace teaches us how to live each day as we turn our backs
        on ungodliness and indulgent lifestyles, [[COMMENT(0)]] and it equips us
        to live self-controlled, upright, godly lives in this present age.   '
      comments:
      - number: 2:12
        content: "  The Greek word for \u201Cungodliness\u201D is singular, while
          the word for \u201Cindulgent lifestyles\u201D is plural. This has led some
          scholars to believe that we are to turn our backs on both the root principle
          of ungodliness and the specific acts that result from ungodliness.     
          These three adjectives\u2014\u201Cself-controlled,\u201D \u201Cupright,\u201D
          and \u201Cgodly\u201D\u2014refer to our behavior, our behavior toward others
          and toward God.    "
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'For we continue to wait for the fulfillment of our hope in the dawning
        splendor [[COMMENT(0)]] of the glory of our great God and Savior, Jesus,
        the Anointed One.   '
      comments:
      - number: 2:13
        content: "  Or \u201Cthe blessed hope and glorious appearing.\u201D The Greek
          word is    (epiphany) and is a nominalized verb that means \u201Ca brightness
          shining all around.\u201D It was through  , the beautiful appearing of
          Christ as a baby, that a wonderful hope was brought to all the world.     
          Or \u201Cour great God and our Savior, Jesus Christ.\u201D Note the four
          great truths of grace in vv.  : (1) Grace is a person\u2014\u201Cour great
          God and Savior, Jesus, the Anointed One.\u201D (2) Grace brings salvation
          for all. (3) Grace educates us on how to live pure lives. (4) Grace brings
          a hope of the manifestation (appearing) of Christ. This is a hope worth
          waiting for.    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: He sacrificed himself for us that he might purchase our freedom from
        every lawless deed and to purify for himself a people who are his very own,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] passionate to do what is beautiful in his eyes.
      comments:
      - number: 2:14
        content: "  We are a people encircled by God himself. The compound Greek
          word    is translated from \u201Caround,\u201D as a circle, and the verb
          \u201Cto be.\u201D It can mean something surrounded by something. It can
          be charted by a dot within a circle. As the circle surrounds the dot, so
          God is around each one of his saints. The circle has the dot all to itself.
          So God has his very own all to himself. We are unique in that we belong
          only to him. Uniquely his, we are monopolized by God, taken into himself
          by grace through faith and surrounded by his love.    "
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: So preach these truths and exhort others to follow them. Be willing
        to expose sin in order to bring correction with full authority, [[COMMENT(0)]]
        without being intimidated  by anyone.
      comments:
      - number: 2:15
        content: "  Or \u201CSpeak these things; exhort or rebuke [speak in order
          to expose sin and bring correction] with all authority.\u201D      Or \u201Cdisregarded.\u201D  "
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Believers\u2019 Conduct in Society"
      title: "Believers\u2019 Conduct in Society"
      number: 1
      content: 'Remind people to respect [[COMMENT(0)]] their governmental leaders
        on every level as law-abiding citizens and to be ready to fulfill their civic
        duty. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:1
        content: "  Or \u201Cbe subject to.\u201D    "
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'And remind them to never tear down anyone with their words or quarrel,
        [[COMMENT(0)]] but instead be considerate, humble, and courteous to everyone. '
      comments:
      - number: 3:2
        content: "  Or \u201Cstrive with others.\u201D The implication is that we
          accept the differences of others and allow people to be who they are and
          not try to make them over into our image of who we think they should be.    "
    - name: '3: The Hymn of Salvation by Grace'
      title: The Hymn of Salvation by Grace
      number: 3
      content: "For it wasn\u2019t that long ago that we behaved foolishly in our
        stubborn disobedience. We were easily led astray as slaves to worldly passions
        and pleasures. We wasted our lives in doing evil, and with hateful jealousy
        we hated others."
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'When the extraordinary compassion of God our Savior [[COMMENT(0)]]and
        his overpowering love suddenly appeared in person,as the brightness of a
        dawning day, '
      comments:
      - number: 3:4
        content: "  Many scholars believe that vv.    are ancient Christian poetry
          or perhaps the words to a hymn.      Implied in the Greek word    (epiphany),
          which means \u201Cto shine forth [brightly] in an appearing.\u201D    "
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: he came to save us.Not because of any virtuous deed that we have donebut
        only because of his extravagant mercy.
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: He saved us,resurrecting us [[COMMENT(0)]] through the washing of
        rebirth.We are made completely new by the Holy Spirit, whom he splashed over
        us richlyby Jesus, the Messiah, our Life Giver.
      comments:
      - number: 3:6
        content: '  As translated from the Aramaic.      All three members of the
          Trinity are mentioned in vv.    and are seen as active participants in
          our salvation.    '
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "So as a gift of his love,and since we are faultless\u2014innocent
        before his face\u2014we can now become heirs of all things,all because of
        an overflowing hope of eternal life."
      comments: []
    - name: '8: Faith Produces Good Works'
      title: Faith Produces Good Works
      number: 8
      content: How true and faithful is this message!I want you to especially emphasize
        [[COMMENT(0)]] these truths, so that those who believe in God will be careful
        to devote themselves to doing good works. It is always beautiful and profitable
        for believers to do good works.
      comments:
      - number: 3:8
        content: "  Or \u201Caffirm strongly,\u201D a hapax legomenon.    "
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'But avoid useless controversies, [[COMMENT(0)]] genealogies,  pointless
        quarrels, and arguments over the law, which will get you nowhere.   '
      comments:
      - number: 3:9
        content: "  The Aramaic can be translated \u201Coffensive debates.\u201D     
          The Aramaic can be translated \u201Ctribal traditions.\u201D      See also 
          .    "
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'After a first and second warning, have nothing more to do with a
        divisive person who refuses to be corrected. '
      comments: []
    - name: "11: Paul\u2019s Coworkers"
      title: "Paul\u2019s Coworkers"
      number: 11
      content: For you know that such a one is entwined with his sin and stands self-condemned.
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "When I send Artemas [[COMMENT(0)]] or Tychicus  to you, be sure to
        meet me at the City of Victory,  for I\u2019ve decided to spend the winter
        there."
      comments:
      - number: 3:12
        content: "  Artemas, or \u201CArtemas of Lystra,\u201D was considered to
          be one of the seventy disciples whom Jesus sent out.      Tychichus, an
          Ephesian, was a beloved coworker of Paul and is mentioned five times in
          the New Testament (here;  ;  ;  ;  ). He was listed among the seventy disciples
          whom Jesus sent out according to Hippolytus of Rome. See Francis Mershman,
          \u201CSt. Tychicus\u201D (1913)  , Charles Herbermann, editor.      Or
          \u201CNicopolis,\u201D a Greek city on the western shore. Nicopolis means
          \u201Cthe City of Victory.\u201D    "
    - name: '13: Conclusion'
      title: Conclusion
      number: 13
      content: Give a generous send-off to Zenas the scribe [[COMMENT(0)]] and Apollos, 
        and send them on their journey with what they need.
      comments:
      - number: 3:13
        content: "  Or \u201Clawyer.\u201D The word translated \u201Clawyer\u201D
          can be used for either Greek or Roman law. Zenas is considered to be one
          of the seventy whom Jesus sent out.      Apollos was a powerful preacher
          and coworker of Paul, who was very influential in the church of Corinth.
          He is listed ten times in the New Testament (;  ;  ;  ,  ;  ;  ). Jerome
          states that Apollos, after Paul\u2019s letters brought healing to the divisions
          of the church in Corinth, returned and became an elder (overseer) in the
          church. See Jerome,  .    "
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: Encourage the believers to be passionately devoted to beautiful works
        of righteousness by meeting the urgent needs of others and not be unfruitful.
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "Everyone here with me sends their loving greetings to you. Greet
        the believers who love us in the faith. May God\u2019s wonderful grace be
        with you all!Love in Christ,Paul  [[COMMENT(0)]]"
      comments:
      - number: 3:15
        content: "  The Aramaic adds, \u201CThe end of the letter written by Paul
          to Titus from Nicopolis, sent by the hand of Zenas and Apollos.\u201D  "
